{
  "query": "To restore peatlands afforested for commercial forestry, how does simply cutting the trees compare to cutting trees and also rewetting the peat?",
  "relevant_summary": "When restoring peatlands afforested for commercial forestry, cutting trees and rewetting peat (Action 1732) shows more comprehensive restoration outcomes compared to only cutting trees (Action 1731). The combined approach increases abundance of wetland-characteristic plants (Action 1732), while tree removal alone only increases cover of some herb species like cottongrasses and sedges (Action 1731). Sphagnum moss responses differ significantly - the combined intervention increases Sphagnum cover (Action 1732), whereas tree removal alone decreases Sphagnum cover over three years (Action 1731). Both approaches increase plant species richness, though one study found the effect is smaller when trees are removed from rewetted plots compared to drained plots (Action 1731). Action 1756 (rewetting alone) demonstrates that water table management is crucial for peatland restoration, showing increased Sphagnum moss cover, reduced tree/shrub cover, and increased herb cover including sedges and cottongrasses.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1732",
    "1731",
    "1756"
  ]
}

