{
  "query": "For degraded peatlands, how do the effects of completely excluding livestock compare to reducing grazing intensity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence from action documents, there are some key differences between completely excluding livestock versus reducing grazing intensity on degraded peatlands:\n\nComplete Livestock Exclusion (Action ID 1734): Multiple studies (10 total) have evaluated livestock exclusion from degraded peatlands. The evidence shows mixed but generally limited effects: most studies found no effect on herb cover including cottongrass and sedges, no consistent effect on Sphagnum moss cover, and no effect on shrub cover in many cases, though some studies showed increased shrub cover. One study found that livestock exclusion increased vegetation biomass but effects varied between wetter and drier areas of bogs.\n\nReducing Grazing Intensity (Action ID 1735): Only one study evaluated this approach specifically in bogs. This study found that lower grazing intensity was associated with greater total vegetation cover, greater shrub cover, greater cottongrass cover (for one species), and higher vegetation biomass.\n\nThe key comparison suggests that reducing grazing intensity shows more consistent positive effects on vegetation cover and biomass based on limited evidence, while complete livestock exclusion shows more variable results with many studies finding no significant effects on key peatland vegetation components.",
  "action_ids": [
    "1734",
    "1735"
