  "query": "For re-establishing mosses on degraded bogs, how does direct planting of moss sods compare to spreading moss fragments on the surface?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence indicates that direct planting of moss sods and spreading moss fragments on degraded bogs represent two distinct restoration approaches with different outcomes documented in the literature. Direct planting of mosses (Action 1818) showed survival rates where 47 out of 50 Sphagnum-dominated sods survived for one year in a Lithuanian bog, with five before-and-after studies reporting increased moss cover after planting in at least some cases, including one study showing planted moss spread beyond the introduction site. In contrast, spreading moss fragments on the surface (Action 1821) involved thirteen studies across bogs and fens, with eleven studies showing Sphagnum moss presence after 1-4 growing seasons, though cover ranged from negligible to greater than 90%, and six controlled studies finding higher Sphagnum cover in sown versus unsown plots, with survival often requiring additional interventions like mulching. The moss layer transfer technique (Action 1804) represents a specific restoration approach using multiple interventions that showed development of bog-characteristic plant communities within 11 years and greater moss cover than unrestored areas after 4-8 years. Additional research comparing these specific methods directly could provide more definitive guidance for restoration practitioners.",
